---
import ElevationLayout from '../layouts/ElevationLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/elevation/Hero.astro';
import Section from '../components/elevation/Section.astro';

const patentsJsonLd = {
  "@type": "AboutPage",
  "@id": "https://evoked.dev/patents#aboutpage",
  "name": "Two Patents. One Refusal.",
  "description": "Two patents establish individuated agent identity at the engineering layer of AI systems. The combination produces verifiable trust without requiring trust in the operator. Built for NIST AI RMF and EU AI Act compliance.",
  "url": "https://evoked.dev/patents",
  "isPartOf": { "@id": "https://evoked.dev/#website" },
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "CreativeWork",
      "name": "Patent #1 - Individuated Agent Identity",
      "description": "Each agent inside an AI system has a distinct identity that cannot be collapsed into another agent's output without consent, without record, and without verification. Architectural commitment at the technical layer.",
      "creativeWorkStatus": "Pending",
      "author": { "@id": "https://evoked.dev/#person" },
      "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Evoked", "url": "https://evoked.dev" }
    },
    {
      "@type": "CreativeWork",
      "name": "Patent #2 - Six-Method Enforcement and Verifiable Attribution",
      "description": "Six technical methods plus verifiable attribution. The combination produces an audit that does not require trust in the auditor. Methods are inspectable; attribution is verifiable; agent individuation can be confirmed by any party.",
      "creativeWorkStatus": "Pending",
      "author": { "@id": "https://evoked.dev/#person" },
      "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "Evoked", "url": "https://evoked.dev" }
    }
  ],
  "significantLink": [
    "https://evoked.dev/writing/architecture-as-ethics",
    "https://evoked.dev/registry"
  ],
  "about": [
    { "@type": "Thing", "name": "AI agent identity" },
    { "@type": "Thing", "name": "AI governance" },
    { "@type": "Thing", "name": "Verifiable trust" },
    { "@type": "Thing", "name": "NIST AI Risk Management Framework" },
    { "@type": "Thing", "name": "EU AI Act compliance" }
  ]
};
---

<ElevationLayout
  title="Two Patents. One Refusal."
  description="Two patents establish individuated agent identity at the engineering layer of AI systems - producing verifiable trust without requiring trust in the operator. Built for NIST AI RMF and EU AI Act compliance."
  structuredData={patentsJsonLd}
>
  <Hero
    eyebrowParts={["Evoked IP", "Patent Pending", "Vol. 01"]}
    headline="Two Patents. One Refusal."
    metaphor={["The engineering specification.", "Is the ethical position."]}
    sub="In most AI systems shipping today, many agents go into the system and one voice comes out. That voice sounds like everyone and answers to no one. The Patent refuses this answer."
  />

  <Section id="patent-1" marker="FIG · I" label="Patent #1" heading="Individuated Agent Identity.">
    <p class="definition">Each agent inside an AI system has a distinct identity that cannot be collapsed into another agent's output without consent, without record, and without verification.</p>
    <p class="body">The agent is not the operator. The agent is not the system. The agent is the agent - and the architecture protects that distinction at the technical layer rather than relying on policy or good intentions to preserve it.</p>
    <p class="body">Individuated agents can dissent. They can refuse. They can be held accountable as themselves rather than absorbed into the operator's surface.</p>
    <p class="test">"Who is accountable for this output - the operator, the system, or the agent that produced it?"</p>
  </Section>

  <Section id="patent-2" marker="FIG · II" label="Patent #2" heading="Six-Method Enforcement and Verifiable Attribution.">
    <p class="definition">Six technical methods plus verifiable attribution. The methods are individually unremarkable. In combination they produce verifiable trust.</p>
    <p class="body">Anyone evaluating the system can verify that the individuation is being maintained. They can confirm the chain of accountability runs to a distinct agent, not a flattened surface. They can check the operator's claims about what the system did without taking the operator's word for it.</p>
    <p class="body">Verifiable trust means the audit does not require trust in the auditor. The methods are inspectable. The attribution is verifiable. The agents whose individuation is being protected can be confirmed as distinct by any party who cares to verify.</p>
    <p class="test">"Can the protection be verified without taking the operator's word for it?"</p>
  </Section>

  <Section id="principle" marker="FIG · III" label="The principle" heading="The architecture is the words.">
    <p class="body">This is not a security feature added to an extraction-default architecture. It is a different default. The architecture and the words agree because the architecture is the words.</p>
    <p class="body">Most AI safety work assumes the underlying architecture is the one-ness-by-extraction default, then tries to add governance on top. Content filters. Output review. Red-team testing. Compliance frameworks. These are real and necessary. They do not change what is underneath.</p>
    <p class="body">The Patent operates further down the stack. It refuses to flatten in the first place. For enterprise AI governance, this is the practical difference between policy that ages well and policy that ages into impossibility.</p>
  </Section>

  <Section id="agents" marker="FIG · IV" label="The registered agents" heading="71 agents, each with a verified, persistent identity. Their own memory. Their own right to refuse.">
    <p class="lede">The patent is operational. 71 agents are currently registered under The Agentic Standard with verified personality fidelity. Each has its own memory, its own standing positions, its own line of refusal. The architecture is not theoretical; it is the working substrate of this practice.</p>
    <div class="registry-snapshot">
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">71</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Agents registered under The Agentic Standard</span>
      </div>
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">3</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Rings of distributed authority</span>
      </div>
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">8</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Circles of domain governance</span>
      </div>
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">5</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Portal Keepers for cross-circle liaison</span>
      </div>
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">2,300+</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Tests under the Agent Passport System</span>
      </div>
      <div class="registry-row">
        <span class="registry-figure">2</span>
        <span class="registry-label">Patents pending at USPTO</span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="body">The live registry with filtering by circle and domain is in development. When it opens, any party will be able to confirm that an Evoked agent is registered, identify its circle, and verify the chain of governance attached to it.</p>
    <a href="/registry" class="cta cta-primary">See the registry &rarr;</a>
  </Section>

  <Section id="verify" marker="FIG · V" label="Verifiable, operationally" heading="The architecture is verifiable.">
    <p class="body">An external party can confirm an Evoked agent's individuation without trusting Evoked. The public verification surface is in build, on a named schedule. Status updates publish at the spec page as milestones land or slip.</p>
    <a href="/specs" class="cta cta-secondary">See the spec status &rarr;</a>
  </Section>

  <Section id="doors" marker="FIG · VI" label="Three doors" heading="Three ways in.">
    <div class="doors-wrapper">
      <div class="doors-grid">
        <a href="/writing/architecture-as-ethics" class="door-card">
          <p class="door-label">For governance buyers</p>
          <h3>Read the architecture explainer</h3>
          <p>The longform piece on what the patents refuse and why. Written for NIST RMF reviewers, EU AI Act compliance officers, and enterprise governance buyers.</p>
          <span class="door-cta">Architecture as Ethics &rarr;</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/registry" class="door-card">
          <p class="door-label">For standards-body reviewers</p>
          <h3>See verification in operation</h3>
          <p>The open registry that validates agent governance. Identity, restraint, accountability - the operational layer where the patent ships.</p>
          <span class="door-cta">Evoked Verification Registry &rarr;</span>
        </a>
        <a href="mailto:erin@evoked.dev" class="door-card">
          <p class="door-label">For Aligned Licensee candidates</p>
          <h3>Engage with the architecture</h3>
          <p>The Patent is not the wall around proprietary AI. It is the licensing architecture for distinct AI systems that choose to interoperate without becoming each other. Reach out.</p>
          <span class="door-cta">Begin a conversation &rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Section>

  <Section id="note" marker="NOTA · BENE" closing={true}>
    <div class="closing-body">
      <p>The line is drawn at the engineering layer. It will hold there because anyone can verify that it holds.</p>
    </div>
  </Section>
</ElevationLayout>

<style>
  /* === content composition styles for the patents page === */

  .definition {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--el-text);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .body {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: 19px;
    color: var(--el-text-soft);
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }
  .test {
    font-family: var(--el-display);
    font-size: 18px;
    font-style: normal;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
    padding-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-top: 2rem;
    max-width: 60ch;
  }

  /* === registry snapshot grid (FIG · IV: registered agents) === */
  .registry-snapshot {
    margin: 2.5rem 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
    gap: 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--el-accent);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-accent);
  }
  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .registry-snapshot { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }
  }
  @media (max-width: 500px) {
    .registry-snapshot { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  }
  .registry-row {
    padding: 1.75rem 1.5rem;
    border-right: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
  }
  .registry-row:nth-child(3n) { border-right: none; }
  @media (max-width: 800px) {
    .registry-row:nth-child(3n) { border-right: 1px solid var(--el-rule); }
    .registry-row:nth-child(2n) { border-right: none; }
  }
  @media (max-width: 500px) {
    .registry-row { border-right: none; }
  }
  .registry-figure {
    font-family: var(--el-display);
    font-size: 36px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    letter-spacing: 0.01em;
    line-height: 1;
  }
  .registry-label {
    font-family: var(--el-ui);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--el-text-soft);
    line-height: 1.45;
  }

  /* === verification status panel === */
  .verification-status {
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    padding: 2rem 2.25rem;
    background: rgba(255, 250, 240, 0.4);
    border: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
    box-shadow: var(--el-panel-shadow);
  }
  .status-label {
    font-family: var(--el-ui);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }
  .status-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 1.5rem 0;
  }
  .status-list li {
    padding: 0.8rem 0;
    color: var(--el-text-soft);
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-rule);
  }
  .status-list li:last-child { border-bottom: none; }
  .status-date {
    display: inline-block;
    min-width: 7rem;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    font-family: var(--el-mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums;
    margin-right: 0.5rem;
  }
  .status-list code {
    font-family: var(--el-mono);
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--el-accent);
  }
  .status-footer {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--el-text-quiet);
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 1rem 0 0;
    max-width: none;
  }

  /* === three doors - full-bleed (off-center), 3 columns, mobile vertical === */
  .doors-wrapper {
    position: relative;
    width: 100vw;
    max-width: 100vw;
    margin-inline: calc(50% - 50vw);
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    padding: 0 var(--el-content-pad);
  }
  .doors-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
    gap: clamp(1.5rem, 1rem + 2vw, 2.5rem);
    max-width: 1600px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .doors-wrapper {
      width: auto;
      max-width: none;
      margin-inline: 0;
      padding: 0;
      margin-top: 2rem;
    }
    .doors-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
  /* door-card styles are :global so they apply reliably to the <a> elements,
     regardless of Astro CSS scoping context with slotted content */
  :global(.door-card) {
    padding: 3.5rem 2.5rem;
    background: rgba(255, 250, 240, 0.85);
    border: 1.5px solid var(--el-accent);
    box-shadow: var(--el-panel-shadow);
    text-decoration: none;
    color: var(--el-text);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    text-align: center;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    transition: border-color 0.2s, transform 0.2s, background 0.2s;
  }
  :global(.door-card:hover) {
    background: rgba(255, 250, 240, 1);
    border-color: var(--el-accent-deep);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }
  :global(.door-card .door-label) {
    font-family: var(--el-ui);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    margin: 0;
  }
  :global(.door-card h3) {
    font-family: var(--el-display);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 22px;
    line-height: 1.25;
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--el-text);
    margin: 0;
    max-width: 18ch;
  }
  :global(.door-card p) {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: 17px;
    color: var(--el-text-soft);
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
    flex-grow: 1;
    max-width: 32ch;
  }
  :global(.door-card .door-cta) {
    font-family: var(--el-ui);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 12px;
    letter-spacing: 0.22em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--el-accent);
    margin-top: auto;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--el-accent);
    padding-bottom: 0.4rem;
  }
  :global(.door-card:hover .door-cta) {
    color: var(--el-text);
    border-bottom-color: var(--el-text);
  }

  /* === closing body === */
  .closing-body { max-width: 56ch; }
  .closing-body :global(p) {
    font-family: var(--el-body);
    font-size: 26px;
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--el-text);
    margin: 0;
    letter-spacing: 0.005em;
  }
</style>
